NASA studies lasers to divert asteroids By DEE ANN DIVIS, Science and=20
Technology Editor

HOUSTON, Oct. 18 (UPI) -- Though there is only a remote chance that an=20
asteroid will strike Earth, the spectacular crash of the Shoemaker-Levy come=
t=20
into the planet Jupiter in 1993 and a razor-thin miss between an asteroid an=
d=20
Earth only last year have sharpened attention on work NASA has been doing to=
=20
prevent impacts and their devastating results.

Even a small asteroid or comet of only about 100 meters can cause tremendous=
=20
damage. It was an asteroid of that size that flattened 2,000 square miles of=
=20
forest in Siberia in 1908. Though there is still only a one in 250,000 chanc=
e=20
of impact, an asteroid that is roughly 1.2 kilometer across -- big enough to=
=20
destroy a continent on impact -- is expected to pass near Earth on Feb. 1,=20
2019.

But it was a comet that did hit that really caught the world's attention.=20
When the comet Shoemaker-Levy struck about 10 years ago, scientists had a=20
ring-side seat as it tore planet-size holes in the golden surface of Jupiter=
=20
in a series of impacts -- impacts big enough to destroy Earth.

"I think it made an impression," Jonathan Campbell, a NASA researcher at=20
Marshall Space Flight Center, told United Press International.

There are roughly 1,000 to 2,000 Earth-orbiting asteroids in the one to=20
10-kilometer class, that is, if they were a smooth ball instead of large=20
lumpy rocks they would be about 1 km across. There are far more smaller=20
asteroids, about 200,000 in the 100-meter class.

Campbell, whose work at NASA is part of Marshall's new National Space Scienc=
e=20
and Technology Center, is studying using a laser to shift the orbit of such=20
dangerous asteroids. Carlos Roithmayr, a scientist at NASA's Langley Researc=
h=20
Center in Hampton, Va., is also looking at using lasers. Both scientists=20
presented their projects Thursday to attendees at the World Space Congress i=
n=20
Houston, Texas.

The lasers would be used to divert -- not destroy -- the threatening rocks.=20
Pulses from the laser would heat the asteroid's surface to such a point that=
=20
a small part of the surface explodes. The explosion does not remove enough o=
f=20
the asteroid to render it harmless, but it does give it a tiny kick to one=20
side. A long series of such little kicks is enough to push the asteroid off=20
its collision course with Earth.

Campbell suggests using a laser based either on the Moon or at one of the=20
libration points -- a spot in space where the gravity of Earth and the Sun=20
cancel each other out and a laser-carrying spacecraft would sit relatively=20
motionless. Roithmayr envisions an option where a laser-bearing spacecraft=20
would travel to the asteroid and then use the laser to turn it aside.

Either system would require extensive advance notice however as the lasers=20
would need to continuously fire at the asteroid for a month or two -- at=20
least to divert it. Such notice involves scanning the skies constantly with=20
telescopes, to identify and map the orbits of asteroids and comets zooming=20
too near the planet.

One good place to place such telescopes would be the moon. Roithmayr=20
described the Comet/Asteroid Protection System, or CAPS, which would include=
=20
as part of the overall protection system a set of telescopes, each with=20
apertures larger than 3 meters, that would placed on the moon. The large=20
telescopes could be placed on tracks to allow them to be configured more=20
flexibly.

